    term: "AI Automation",
    slug: "ai-automation",
    definition: "AI automation is the use of artificial intelligence to execute repeatable business tasks without manual intervention. Unlike traditional rule-based automation, AI automation can interpret unstructured data, adapt to variations in input, and make routine decisions based on defined criteria. It is the core technology enabling small and medium-sized businesses to recover operational capacity without adding headcount.",
    simpleExplanation: "AI automation means teaching a computer system to handle tasks that a person used to do manually, like sorting emails, filling in forms, scheduling appointments, or sending follow-up messages. The AI follows the rules you set but can also handle variations that traditional software cannot, such as reading a document and extracting the right information even when the format changes.",
    businessExample: "An immigration consulting firm receives client documents through email, portal uploads, and physical mail. Without AI automation, an administrator manually downloads, categorizes, files, and logs each document. With AI automation, the system extracts attachments from all sources, classifies document type, files in the correct client folder, and notifies the assigned consultant. The administrator reviews a daily exception report instead of processing each document individually.",
    risksAndMisconceptions: "The most common misconception is that AI automation is plug-and-play. In practice, AI automation requires process documentation before implementation. Automating a poorly understood process creates automated chaos. Another misconception is that AI automation replaces employees. In most SMB implementations, AI automation recovers staff capacity for higher-value work rather than eliminating positions.",
