    term: "AI Workflow",
    slug: "ai-workflow",
    definition: "An AI workflow is an end-to-end business process that uses artificial intelligence to connect, coordinate, and execute multiple tasks as a unified sequence. AI workflows manage triggers, decision points, handoffs, and exception routing with minimal human intervention, eliminating the gaps between tasks where work traditionally stalls.",
    simpleExplanation: "An AI workflow is a complete chain of tasks that AI handles from start to finish. Instead of automating one task at a time, a workflow connects all the steps. For example, when a client submits a form, the workflow automatically processes the data, creates a file, notifies the right person, and schedules a follow-up, all without anyone manually moving information between steps.",
    businessExample: "A dental clinic receives appointment requests through phone, text, and web. An AI workflow captures the request regardless of channel, checks provider availability, schedules the appointment, sends a confirmation, verifies insurance eligibility, and sends a reminder before the appointment. If the patient cancels, the workflow automatically contacts waitlisted patients to fill the gap.",
    risksAndMisconceptions: "The most common mistake is automating a workflow without first optimizing it. If the current process has unnecessary steps or inefficient routing, AI will automate those inefficiencies perfectly. Always document and improve the process before automating it. Another risk is building workflows that are too complex initially. Start simple and add branches incrementally.",
    implementationAdvice: "Map the workflow end-to-end before building anything. Identify every trigger, decision point, action, and exception. Start with the most common scenario as a linear workflow. Add exception handling after the core flow is stable. Build monitoring into every workflow to track completion rates, processing times, and error frequencies.",
    expertPerspective: "Ikram Rana of Barrana.ai explains: \"Systems matter more than tools. A single well-designed AI workflow that handles a process from start to finish is worth more than five separate AI tools that each handle one step. The value is in the connections, not the components.\"",
