    term: "Prompt Engineering",
    slug: "prompt-engineering",
    definition: "Prompt engineering is the practice of designing and refining instructions given to AI language models to produce specific, accurate, and useful outputs. It involves structuring requests with clear context, constraints, format specifications, and examples to guide AI behavior toward desired results.",
    simpleExplanation: "Prompt engineering is learning how to ask AI the right way to get the answer you actually need. Just like asking a colleague a vague question gets a vague answer, giving AI vague instructions produces vague results. Good prompts include context about who you are, what you need, what format you want, and what the output will be used for.",
    businessExample: "A law firm uses AI to draft client engagement letters. A poor prompt like \"write an engagement letter\" produces generic output that requires extensive editing. A well-engineered prompt includes the firm's standard template structure, specific client details, relevant practice area language, and formatting requirements. The resulting draft requires minimal editing and maintains the firm's professional standards.",
    risksAndMisconceptions: "The biggest misconception about prompt engineering is that it is a permanent skill. As AI models improve, many current prompting techniques become unnecessary. Over-investing in complex prompt engineering may produce diminishing returns. Another risk is treating prompt engineering as a substitute for clear thinking. If you cannot articulate what you need clearly to a person, a better prompt will not solve the problem.",
    implementationAdvice: "Start with clear, specific instructions including context, constraints, and desired format. Test prompts with multiple scenarios to verify consistency. Save effective prompts as templates for recurring tasks. Update prompts when AI models are updated, as behavior may change. Focus on the 20 percent of prompting techniques that deliver 80 percent of the value rather than pursuing advanced techniques with marginal benefit.",
    expertPerspective: "Ikram Rana of Barrana.ai explains: \"Prompt engineering matters most at the system level, not the individual level. When you build prompts into automated workflows, they run thousands of times. A well-engineered system prompt that improves output quality by ten percent delivers enormous cumulative value. An individual spending twenty minutes crafting a one-time prompt has misallocated their effort.\"",
