    term: "AI Governance",
    slug: "ai-governance",
    definition: "AI governance is the framework of policies, processes, and accountability structures that ensure AI systems operate safely, ethically, and within regulatory requirements. For businesses, AI governance defines who is responsible for AI systems, what decisions AI can make, how those decisions are monitored, and what happens when AI produces incorrect or harmful outcomes.",
    simpleExplanation: "AI governance is the set of rules your business creates for how AI is used. It answers questions like: Who is responsible when AI makes a mistake? What is AI allowed to decide on its own? How do we check that AI is working correctly? What do we do when something goes wrong? It is the business equivalent of safety protocols for a powerful tool.",
    businessExample: "A financial advisory firm implements AI for client portfolio recommendations. Their governance framework defines what recommendations AI can make, requires human approval above certain thresholds, creates audit trails for every recommendation, assigns a compliance officer to review AI accuracy monthly, and establishes a process for correcting errors and notifying affected clients.",
    risksAndMisconceptions: "The most dangerous misconception is that AI governance is only for large enterprises. Every business using AI in operational decisions needs governance proportionate to its usage. Another risk is creating governance policies that exist on paper but are not integrated into daily operations. Governance is only effective when it is part of the workflow, not a separate document that nobody follows.",
    implementationAdvice: "Establish five pillars: accountability with named owners for each AI system, transparency with documented decision processes, boundaries with explicit operational limits, monitoring with active oversight, and remediation with defined error correction processes. Start simple and proportionate to your AI usage. Review and update governance quarterly for new implementations.",
