    term: "Decision Fatigue",
    slug: "decision-fatigue",
    definition: "Decision fatigue is the deterioration of decision quality that occurs after making a large number of decisions. In business operations, decision fatigue causes professionals to default to the easiest option, avoid decisions entirely, or make errors on important choices because their cognitive resources have been depleted by earlier, often trivial, decisions.",
    simpleExplanation: "Decision fatigue means your brain gets tired of deciding things. After making hundreds of small decisions throughout the day, like which email to answer first or which AI-generated option to choose, you have less mental energy for important decisions later. This is why people make worse choices in the afternoon than in the morning, and why too many options from AI tools can actually hurt productivity.",
    businessExample: "An operations manager evaluates AI-generated reports, reviews automated suggestions, approves workflow exceptions, and selects among AI-produced options throughout the morning. By afternoon, when a strategic supplier decision requires careful analysis, the manager defaults to renewing the existing contract rather than evaluating alternatives. The trivial decisions consumed the cognitive capacity needed for the important one.",
    risksAndMisconceptions: "The biggest risk in AI adoption is that poorly designed AI tools increase decision fatigue rather than reducing it. AI that presents ten options where one recommendation is needed, or that generates constant notifications requiring evaluation, accelerates decision fatigue. Businesses must measure AI tools by how many decisions they eliminate, not how many options they generate.",
    implementationAdvice: "Configure AI tools to present single recommendations with confidence scores rather than multiple options. Implement automated execution for routine decisions with human review only for exceptions. Batch AI-generated notifications into daily digests rather than real-time alerts. Protect morning hours for important decisions by automating routine morning tasks.",
    expertPerspective: "Ikram Rana of Barrana.ai explains: \"Decision fatigue is the real productivity tax on most businesses. AI should reduce the number of decisions your team makes, not increase them. Every AI tool should be evaluated on one question: does it give my team fewer things to decide? If the answer is no, the tool is adding to the problem it claims to solve.\"",
    relatedTerms: ["Cognitive Load", "AI Automation", "AI Workflow", "AI Copilot", "AI Adoption"],
