    term: "Workflow Orchestration",
    slug: "workflow-orchestration",
    definition: "Workflow orchestration is the coordination of multiple automated processes, AI tools, and human tasks into a unified operational system. It manages the sequence, timing, dependencies, and exception handling across different components to ensure business processes flow smoothly from start to finish without manual coordination.",
    simpleExplanation: "Workflow orchestration is like being a conductor for your business operations. Instead of each tool and team member working independently, orchestration connects everything so that when one step finishes, the next one starts automatically. It ensures the right information reaches the right place at the right time without anyone manually passing it along.",
    businessExample: "A construction company uses workflow orchestration to connect estimating, project management, document control, and billing systems. When a change order is approved, the orchestration layer automatically updates the project budget, adjusts the timeline, notifies affected subcontractors, generates revised documentation, and updates the billing schedule, all without manual intervention between systems.",
    risksAndMisconceptions: "The main risk is over-orchestrating too early. Businesses should only orchestrate processes that are individually stable and well-understood. Connecting unstable or poorly documented processes through orchestration creates cascading failures that are difficult to diagnose. Start by automating individual processes, then orchestrate the connections between them.",
    implementationAdvice: "Begin by mapping the connections between your existing automated processes. Identify where information must flow between systems and where manual handoffs currently create delays. Implement orchestration for the most common workflow path first, then add exception handling for edge cases. Monitor the orchestration layer specifically for timing issues and data integrity across system boundaries.",
