    term: "AI Strategy",
    slug: "ai-strategy",
    definition: "AI strategy is a business's deliberate plan for how artificial intelligence will be adopted, implemented, and managed to achieve specific operational and competitive objectives. It defines which processes will use AI, in what order, with what resources, and how success will be measured, preventing the ad hoc tool accumulation that characterizes most failed AI initiatives.",
    simpleExplanation: "AI strategy is having a plan for how your business will use AI instead of just buying whatever tools look interesting. It means deciding what problems you are solving, which processes to automate first, how to measure success, and how to expand over time. Without a strategy, businesses end up with expensive AI tools that nobody uses effectively.",
    businessExample: "A mid-sized law firm develops an AI strategy that prioritizes client intake automation first for immediate revenue impact, then document drafting for attorney productivity, then billing automation for cash flow improvement. Each phase has defined success metrics and a timeline. This strategic approach delivers measurable results at each stage rather than attempting everything simultaneously.",
    risksAndMisconceptions: "The primary risk is confusing AI strategy with AI tool selection. Strategy determines which problems to solve and in what order. Tool selection happens after strategy is defined. Businesses that start with tools instead of strategy accumulate technology without direction. Another risk is creating a strategy that is too ambitious. Effective AI strategy for SMBs focuses on two to three high-impact implementations rather than comprehensive transformation.",
